<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-172-528  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 172 528.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Executive  Winter 1989 v2 n1 p18(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Nelson fights computer crime in the House. (Rep. Bill Nelson,D-FL, US House of Representatives) (interview)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Beamer, Wayne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Bill Nelson, a former astronaut and a member of the House ofRepresentatives, has been involved in computer crime legislationfor more than a decade.andP;  As a member of Florida's House ofRepresentatives in 1978, Nelson helped bring about the passage ofthe first computer crime law in the nation.andP;  In 1984, as a memberof the US House, he led the effort that established the firstfederal computer crime law.andP;  Nelson discusses his career as anastronaut and what led him to become involved in computer crimelegislation.andP;  Nelson attributes the low prosecution rate ofcomputer crime to embarrassment on the part of companies reluctantto admit their security has been breached.andP;  He believes thatprosecution will increase as the computer becomes even moreintegral a part of business and society.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer CrimeLegislationInterviewUnited States. Congress. House.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Bill Nelson. (portrait)Person:    Nelson, Bill (interviews).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>